'''Abu 'Ali Muhammad al-Jubba'i'''  ({{lang-ar|ÿ£ÿ®Ÿà ÿπŸÑŸâ ŸÖÿ≠ŸÖÿØ ÿßŸÑÿ¨ÿ®ÿßÿ¶Ÿä}}; died c. 915) was an [[Arab people|Arab]]  [[Mu'tazili]] [[theologian]] and [[philosopher]] of the 10th century. Born in [[Khuzistan]], he studied in [[Basra]] where he trained [[Abu al-Hasan al-Ash'ari]], who went on to found his own theological tradition, and his son [[Abd al-Salam al-Jubba'i]].<ref>''The Cambridge History of Medieval Philosophy'', Volume II, ed. Robert Passnau (2010), p.918</ref>

