{{confusing|date=September 2014|reason=it does not resemble a biographical article, and is simply couple of random pieces put together}}

'''Apollonides''' (fl. 46 BC) was a [[Stoicism|Stoic]] [[philosopher]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ancientlibrary.com/smith-bio/0246.html|title=Dictionary of Greek and Roman Biography and Mythology, page 237 (v. 1)|publisher=}}</ref> He was a friend and companion of [[Cato the Younger]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=E82oRzHYLhMC&pg=PA32&lpg=PA32&dq=Apollonides+cato&source=bl&ots=x2Z8CTa_NG&sig=kBCOxCL-S5kPZBZNbsr6mdc3fPE&hl=en&sa=X&ei=QsEiVJjUJsr3yQSdpoCIBA&ved=0CDoQ6AEwBg#v=onepage&q=Apollonides%20cato&f=false|title=The Philosophers of the Ancient World|publisher=}}</ref>

The sole record of Apollonides is within [[Plutarch's]] account of Cato the Younger in ''[[Parallel Lives]]''. From this account, there is evidence that after the [[Battle of Thapsus]], Apollonides was present with Cato at [[Utica, Tunisia|Utica]]. During this time, Cato ordered a young man named Statyllius to leave Utica. When Statyllius refused, Cato appointed Apollonides and Demetrius  the [[Peripatetic school|Peripatetic]] to "reduce this man's swollen pride and restore him to conformity with his best interests."<ref>Plut. ''Cat.'' 65</ref> When Cato later inquired if Statyllius was sent off, Apollonides responded:
{{quote|text="By no means... although we reasoned much with him; but he is lofty and unbending, and says he will remain and do whatever thou doest."<ref>Plut. ''Cat.'' 66</ref>}}

In preparation for his [[suicide]], Cato had everyone present leave his side, with the exception of Apollonides and Demetrius.<ref>Plut. ''Cat.'' 69</ref> Cato's character is emphasized in this choice as "it says a great deal about Cato that he saved his last real conversation for his philosophers, not his son."<ref>Goodman & Soni. ''Rome's Last Citizen: The Life and Legacy of Cato, Mortal Enemy of Caesar,'' p. 268</ref>

