{{Infobox religious building | name = Sanshin-ji | native_name = | image = Sanshin-ji Spring.jpg | image_size = | alt = | caption = | map_type = | map_size = | map_alt = | map_caption = | location = 1728 S Olive St. [[Bloomington, Indiana]] | coordinates = {{coord|39.147735|-86.519626|display=inline,title}} | religious_affiliation = [[S≈çt≈ç]] | deity = [[≈öƒÅkyamuni]] (Buddha) | country = United States | functional_status = | website = [http://www.sanshinji.org Official Website] | founded_by = [[Shohaku Okumura]] | year_completed = 1996 }}'''Sanshin Zen Community''' is a [[Soto Zen]] [[Sangha (Buddhism)|sangha]] based at the temple '''Sanshin-ji''' in [[Bloomington, Indiana]] founded by [[Shohaku Okumura]].<ref name="home">{{cite web|title=Welcome to Sanshin Zen Community|url=http://sanshinji.org/home/|publisher=Sanshin Zen Community|accessdate=April 24, 2013|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130520202311/http://sanshinji.org/home/|archivedate=May 20, 2013|df=}}</ref>
==History== The Sanshin Zen Community was incorporated as an organization in 1996 by [[Shohaku Okumura]] after serving as the interim abbot of the [[Minnesota Zen Meditation Center]] since 1992. He chose the name {{nihongo|sanshin|‰∏âÂøÉ|sanshin}}, meaning "three minds", in reference to [[Eihei Dogen]]'s teaching from the ''[[Tenzo Ky≈çkun]]'' of the three minds a Zen student should cultivate: magnanimous mind, parental mind, and joyful mind. However, the following year the S≈çt≈ç-shumucho, the administrative body of [[S≈çt≈ç]] Zen in Japan, asked Okumura to head the Soto Zen Education Center in San Francisco, to which he agreed, delaying his plans to found his own temple. While still serving in that position, his friend and Buddhist Studies scholar John McRae, recommended locating his temple in [[Bloomington, Indiana]]. By 2002 land had been purchased and a local architect employed to design a combined zendo and living space for the Okumura family.<ref>{{citation|last=Haederle|first=Michael|title=Profile: Sanshin Zen Community|newspaper=[[Lion's Roar (magazine)|Lion's Roar]]|year=2013|date=12 November 2013|url=https://www.lionsroar.com/profile-sanshin-zen-community/|access-date=2018-05-08}}</ref>
The [[Sangha (Buddhism)|sangha]] follows a modified monastic schedule<ref>{{cite web|title=Daily Schedule|url=http://sanshinji.org/schedule/|publisher=Sanshin Zen Community|accessdate=April 24, 2013|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130308025138/http://sanshinji.org/schedule/|archivedate=March 8, 2013|df=}}</ref> with a retreat each month.<ref name="home"/> Sanshin is one of the few Zen communities offering a sesshin ('without toys') in the style of Uchiyama-roshi, featuring 14 hours of zazen per day with no ceremonies, work, or Dharma talks. Okumura also offers regular Genzo-e retreats devoted to studying one of the fascicles of [[D≈çgen|D≈çgen Zenji's]] [[Sh≈çb≈çgenz≈ç]];<ref name="home"/> he also travels to give them at other prominent North American Zen Centers.<ref name="home"/> Since the founding of Sanshin-ji, Okumura has ordained multiple students as priests, some of whom have gone on to found their own temples and monasteries elsewhere. For example, Okumura's student Densho Quintero had founded the Comunidad Soto Zen de Colombia in [[Bogot√°]] in 1989, while [[Sh≈çry≈´ Bradley]] founded the [[Gyobutsuji Zen Monastery]] in Arkansas in 2011. In early 2016 it was announced that the founding abbot Shohaku Okumura would retire in 2023 to be gradually succeeded by his student [[Hoko Karnegis]], who would serve as vice abbot in the interim.<ref>{{citation|last=Sperry|first=Rod Meade|title=Hoko Karnegis to succeed Sanshin Zen Community abbot Shohaku Okumura|newspaper=[[Lion's Roar (magazine)|Lion's Roar]]|year=2016|date=6 January 2016|url=https://www.lionsroar.com/hoko-karnegis-to-succeed-sanshin-zen-community-abbot-shohaku-okumura/|access-date=2018-05-08}}</ref>
===Lineage=== The style of practice at this [[zendo]] follows the lineage of [[Kosho Uchiyama]]-roshi<ref name="lineage">{{cite web|title=Our Lineage|url=http://sanshinji.org/teachers/|publisher=Sanshin Zen Community|accessdate=April 24, 2013|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130508025116/http://sanshinji.org/teachers/|archivedate=May 8, 2013|df=}}</ref> and his teacher, [[Kodo Sawaki]]-roshi,<ref name="lineage"/> who founded [[Antaiji]] temple,<ref name="lineage"/> and greatly simplified the [[Soto Zen]] forms used there.
