{{Infobox philosopher |region = [[Western philosophy]] |era = [[Contemporary philosophy|21st century Philosophy]] |color = |image = |name = '''Susan Meld Shell''' |birth_date = {{Birth date and age|mf=yes|1948|3|24}} |birth_place = |death_date = |death_place = |school_tradition = [[German idealism]] | institutions = [[Boston College]] |main_interests = [[political philosophy]], [[Kantian philosophy]] | thesis_title = | thesis_url = | thesis_year = | doctoral_advisor = | doctoral_students = |notable_ideas = | spouse = | education = | alma_mater = [[Harvard University]] (Ph.D.), [[Cornell University]] (B.A.) |influences = [[Kant]], [[Rousseau]] |influenced = |awards = [[NEH Fellowship]], [[Bradley Foundation Fellowship]], [[ACLS Fellowship]] |website = }}
'''Susan Meld Shell''' (born March 24, 1948) is an American philosopher and Professor and Chair of the Department of Political Sicence at [[Boston College]]. She is known for her research on [[Kantian philosophy]].<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Riley|first1=Patrick|title=On Susan Shell's "Kant's Theory of Property"|journal=[[Political Theory (journal)|Political Theory]]|volume=6|issue=1|pages=91‚Äì99|doi=10.1177/009059177800600106|url=http://journals.sagepub.com/doi/abs/10.1177/009059177800600106?journalCode=ptxa|accessdate=25 February 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Susan Shell, Boston College ¬∑ The Murphy Institute|url=http://murphy.tulane.edu/events/1178/1054|website=[[Murphy Institute]]|accessdate=25 February 2018|language=en}}</ref>
==Books== * ''Kant and the Limits of Autonomy'' (Harvard University Press, 2009) * ''The Embodiment of Reason: Kant on Spirit, Generation and Community'' (University of Chicago Press, 1996) * ''The Rights of Reason: A Study of Kant's Philosophy and Politics'' (University of Toronto Press, 1980) * ''America at Risk: Threats to Liberal Self-Government in an Age of Uncertainty'', edited by Susan Shell and [[Robert K. Faulkner]] (University of Michigan Press, 2009) * ''Kant's 'Observations' and 'Remarks': A Critical Guide'', edited by Susan Shell and [[Richard Velkley]] (Cambridge University Press, 2012).
